Suppose you added a wrong change.
Commit history:
Commit1 → Commit2 → Commit3
If Commit3 is wrong, run:
git revert <commit-id>
Git will create a new commit that cancels Commit3 changes.
The difference is about setting upstream (tracking) branch.

1️⃣ git push origin master

This command pushes the master branch to the remote repository.

git push origin master

Meaning:

origin → remote repository

master → branch name

It only pushes the code.

Next time when you push, you must again specify:

git push origin master
2️⃣ git push -u origin master
git push -u origin master

-u means --set-upstream

This command:

Pushes the branch

Links local branch with remote branch

So Git remembers the remote branch.

